5|$|The album {{received}} mixed reviewssome critics {{claimed it}} was fresh and a new sound, while others argued it was very similar to music already available. Desolate North has an extremely slow rhythm and has only limited vocals. The music is interspersed with various woodland sounds, such as running water and footsteps. The natural imagery used on the album is reminiscent of that used in <b>black</b> <b>metal,</b> but the music is closer to ambient.|$|E
50|$|In late 1997, Kristoffer Rygg invited keyboardist, sound conceptualist, and {{composer}} Tore Ylwizaker into the collective, {{and together they}} created a strategy for The Blake Album. Musically, the album transcended <b>black</b> <b>metal’s</b> aesthetics to create a genre-defying work and employed everything from ambient and classical sounds to industrial, prog metal, and art rock. The title alone being a loud signal that Ulver had changed somewhat.|$|R
